figgy.title: Try to repair files with failed fixity

comments.body:
Testing strategy:

1. An object where we've corrupted the local isilon file
    a.  Run cloud fixity check on the FileSet with `CloudFixity::FixityRequest.queue_resource_check!`. Result: success
    b. Run local fixity check on the FileSet with `LocalFixityJob.perform_now`. We saw it enqueue and perform the RepairLocalFixityJob. Downloaded the file before and after. Result: successful repair.
3. An object where we've replaced the cloud file with a different tiff
    a.  Run local fixity check. Result: success
    b. Run cloud fixity check. Result: The file on the cloud is still the broken file. The health status report says "healthy". And the cloud fixity display says "failed."
5. An object where we've both corrupted the local isilon file and replaced the cloud file with a different tiff


TODO:
* why did cloud fixity say "failed" instead of "repairing"? Go look at the file set member template.
* why did the health report continue saying "healthy"? Is it getting the right events?
*

pdc_describe.title: Describe Staging: Error message when trying to approve

comments.body:
It looks like the serialize to DataCite does not handle unknown types correctly. The log shows the following error:

```
I, [2023-05-08T14:50:10.435691 #1147]  INFO -- : [a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] Processing by WorksController#approve as HTML

I, [2023-05-08T14:50:10.480323 #1147]  INFO -- : [a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] Completed 500 Internal Server Error in 44ms (ActiveRecord: 6.7ms | Allocations: 6772)
F, [2023-05-08T14:50:10.482097 #1147] FATAL -- : [a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0]   
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] ArgumentError (Type cannot be nil):
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0]   
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/pdc_serialization/datacite.rb:133:in `new'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/pdc_serialization/datacite.rb:133:in `block in individual_contributors_from_work_resource'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/pdc_serialization/datacite.rb:132:in `map'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/pdc_serialization/datacite.rb:132:in `individual_contributors_from_work_resource'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/pdc_serialization/datacite.rb:91:in `new_from_work_resource'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/pdc_metadata/resource.rb:72:in `to_xml'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/work.rb:709:in `doi_attribute_xml'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/work.rb:716:in `doi_attributes'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/work.rb:689:in `publish_doi'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/models/work.rb:577:in `publish'
[a6f7301d-aefa-4be9-b974-b95adee2d5f0] app/controllers/works_controller.rb:213:in `approve'
```

We noticed that the role was blank in the additional contributors, perhaps because the existing role in the record did not match the valid types in the DataCite gem. This is the root of the problem. Selecting a role (the drop down has the valid values) allowed the record to be approved.

I corrected several records that had bad or missing data for DataCite (used PR #1132 to detect them) but noticed that there are two records in staging without a DOI, not even a draft DOI:
* https://pdc-describe-staging.princeton.edu/describe/works/277  
* https://pdc-describe-staging.princeton.edu/describe/works/289
